rkey, but the city has been falsified in its presentation by the Turkish government in order to erase Armenian history in the wake of the Armenian Genocide. This timely publication also raises questions about the preservation of major historic monuments in the face of post atrocity campaigns of cultural erasure.   Originally written by young priest Krikor Balakian in 1910, just a few years before the Armenian genocide, this book offers a powerful and poignant counterpart to Balakian's acclaimed genocide memoir Armenian Golgotha. This new translation by the author's great-nephew, Pulitzer Prize-winning poet Peter Balakian, eloquently renders the book's vivid descriptions and lyrical prose into English. Including a new introduction that explores Ani's continued relevance in the twenty-first century, The Ruins of Ani will give readers a new appreciation for this lost city's status as a pinnacle of both Armenian civilization and human achievement.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Dez 2019) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aArkun, Aram, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt.1 aBalakian, Peter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut.1 aBalakian, Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP eBook-Package Frontlist 2019z978311065352640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978802940423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781978802940.jpg  a978-3-11-065352-6  RUP eBook-Package Frontlist 2019b2019  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG